distributions.documentation: Distribution function(s) of one or many particle species. This structure is specifically designed to handle non-Maxwellian distribution function generated during heating and current drive, typically solved using a Fokker-Planck calculation perturbed by a heating scheme (e.g. IC, EC, LH, NBI, or alpha heating) and then relaxed by Coloumb collisions.

distributions.code.documentation: Generic decription of the code-specific parameters for the code that has produced this IDS

distributions.code.output_flag.documentation: Output flag : 0 means the run is successful, other values mean some difficulty has been encountered, the exact meaning is then code specific. Negative values mean the result shall not be used.

distributions.code.parameters.documentation: List of the code specific parameters in XML format

distributions.distribution.documentation: Set of distribution functions. Every distribution function has to be associated with only one particle species, specified in distri_vec/species/, but there could be multiple distribution function for each species. In this case, the fast particle populations should be superposed

distributions.distribution[:].fast_filte.documentation: Description of how the fast and the thermal particle populations are separated
Energy at which the fast and thermal particle populations were separated, as a function of radius
Index in the error_description list for "energy"
Method used to separate the fast and thermal particle population (indices TBD)
Integer identifier (enumeration index within a list)

distributions.distribution[:].ggd.documentation: Distribution represented using the ggd, for various time slices

distributions.distribution[:].ggd[:].exp.documentation: Distribution function expanded into a vector of successive approximations. The first element in the vector (expansion(1)) is the zeroth order distribution function, while the K:th element in the vector (expansion(K)) is the K:th correction, such that the total distribution function is a sum over all elements in the expansion vector.
Values of the distribution function expansion, for various grid subsets
Interpolation coefficients, to be used for a high precision evaluation of the physical quantity with finite elements, provided per element in the grid subset (first dimension).
Index in the error_description list for "coefficients"
Index of the grid used to represent this quantity
Index of the grid subset the data is provided on
One scalar value is provided per element in the grid subset.
Index in the error_description list for "values"

distributions.distribution[:].gyro_type.documentation: Defines how to interpret the spatial coordinates: 1 = given at the actual particle birth point; 2 =given at the gyro centre of the birth point

distributions.distribution[:].is_delta_f.documentation: If is_delta_f=1, then the distribution represents the deviation from a Maxwellian; is_delta_f=0, then the distribution represents all particles, i.e. the full-f solution

Integer identifier (enumeration index within a list)

distributions.ids_properties.documentation: Interface Data Structure properties. This element identifies the node above as an IDS

distributions.ids_properties.homogeneous.documentation: 1 if the time of this IDS is homogeneous. In this case, the time values for this IDS are stored in ../time just below the root of this IDS. Otherwise, the time values are stored in the various time fields at lower levels in the tree.

distributions.ids_properties.provider.documentation: Name of the person in charge of producing this data

distributions.ids_properties.source.documentation: Source of the data (any comment describing the origin of the data : code, path to diagnostic signals, processing method, ...)

distributions.vacuum_toroidal_field.b0.documentation: Vacuum toroidal field at R0 [T]; Positive sign means anti-clockwise when viewing from above. The product R0B0 must be consistent with the b_tor_vacuum_r field of the tf IDS.
